Today I will be trying to do a principal component analysis (PCA) on the Bobs Burgers tidy tuesday dataset.

Setup

To do this I will use a few new packages: corrr, ggcorrplot, FactoMineR, and factoextra.

Load libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(corrr)
library(ggcorrplot)
library(FactoMineR)
library(factoextra)

Load the data

tuesdata <- tidytuesdayR::tt_load(2024, week = 47)
episode_metrics <- tuesdata$episode_metrics

Analysis

Clean the Data

First, I want to exclude the seasons from this analysis as I will be treating it like the âspeciesâ lol

clean <- episode_metrics %>%
  select(!season)

The data consists of multiple numeric variables, each on different scales. Therefore, I have to normalize the data first. I will use z-score normalization to do this:

norm <- scale(clean) # normalize the data (z score normalization)
#head(norm)

PCA

These packages have nice built in functions to do this :) so doing PCA is super easy:

data.pca <- princomp(norm) # pca analysis on normalized data

Once we have this data, we can look at a summary table of the PCs:

summary(data.pca) # summary of PCA showing stats of every PC generated
## Importance of components:
##                           Comp.1    Comp.2    Comp.3    Comp.4     Comp.5
## Standard deviation     1.6366867 1.1281476 0.9856615 0.9734070 0.73193074
## Proportion of Variance 0.3840897 0.1824876 0.1393019 0.1358597 0.07681421
## Cumulative Proportion  0.3840897 0.5665773 0.7058793 0.8417389 0.91855314
##                           Comp.6     Comp.7
## Standard deviation     0.6699026 0.34534396
## Proportion of Variance 0.0643465 0.01710036
## Cumulative Proportion  0.9828996 1.00000000

Looking at the PCA summary, this shows that the first PC explains ~38% of dta, the next explains about ~19% (total 57%). so doesnât explain the data suuuuuuper well but explains the majority

We can also look at the loading matrix for PC1+PC2

data.pca$loadings[, 1:2] # look at loading matrix for first two PCs

So pc1 has high positive values (~.5) for dialogue density and average length, with only a slight negative value (-.05) for unique words.

PC2 has super high (~.7) positive value for unique words, and high negative value (~.45) for exclamation ratio.

Not super sure how to interpret these results, but intersting that PC2 is really dominated by the unique words.

Plotting

We can plot the data in various ways to help visualize!

Scree Plot

This plot basically shows how much of the data each PC explains. It is typically used to see how many PCs to retain.

fviz_eig(data.pca, addlabels = TRUE) # scree plot

Seems in my case maybe it would be better to retain 1-4 since pc 2, 3, and 4 are kinda similar in value? idk really not super versed in how to determine this lol iâll just keep it to pc1 + 2.

Biplot

Next is a biplot of the attributes!

fviz_pca_var(data.pca, col.var = "black") # biplot

So average length, dialogue density, question ratio, and sentiment variance all are positively correlated with eachother since they are going the same direction. And looks like average length is the most well-represented variable (furthest from the origin)

Contribution of each variable

This plot is to show the cos2 values of each variable to PC 1&2. Basically, shows how much PC1&2 represents each variable.

fviz_cos2(data.pca, choice = "var", axes = 1:2) # contribution of each variable. so avg length is the most well represented variable in pc1 and 2

This plot shows that average length is the variable most well represented by PC1&2.

Plotting of individuals on PC axes

Now for the PCA plot we are all probably most familiar with:

fviz_pca_ind(data.pca,
             label = "none", # hide individual labels
             habillage = episode_metrics$season, # color by groups
             addEllipses = TRUE # Concentration ellipses
             )

Itâs kinda messy, but you can see that most seasons are grouped tightly, with season 13 and 14 being outliers and grouping separate. So shows that most seasons are pretty similar, except s13 and s14 (which are more similar to each other than the other seasons). Also does seem s1&2 slightly peel off from the other in-between seasons, but not to the degree s13&14 do.
